ans that a creature suffers no harm, or reduced harm, from an effect. A failed save usually means that a creature suffers the full effect of the hazard.']\n['THE THREE TYPES OF CHECKS', 'What are ability checks used for?', \"Ability checks are used when you want to do something that isn't covered by an attack roll or save.\"]\n['THE THREE TYPES OF CHECKS', 'How do you make an ability check?', 'To make an ability check, roll a d20 and add the appropriate ability modifier.']\n['THE THREE TYPES OF CHECKS', 'What happens if the total of an ability check equals or exceeds the DC?', 'If the total of an ability check equals or exceeds the DC, the ability check is a success and you overcome the challenge.']\n['THE THREE TYPES OF CHECKS', 'What happens if the total of an ability check is less than the DC?', 'If the total of an ability check is less than the DC, the ability check is a failure and you make no progress toward the objective, or you make some progress but also suffer a setback, as determined by the GM.']\n['THE THREE TYPES OF CHECKS', 'What is a contest?', 'A contest is a special form of ability check that occurs when your efforts are directly opposed by someone else.']\n['THE THREE TYPES OF CHECKS', 'How do you determine the winner of a contest?', 'Every participant in a contest makes an ability check. The participant with the highest check result wins the contest and either succeeds at the action or prevents other participants from succeeding.']\n['THE THREE TYPES OF CHECKS', 'What happens if there is a tie in a contest?', 'If there is a tie in a contest, the situation remains the same.']\n['THE THREE TYPES OF CHECKS', 'What is a passive check?', \"A passive check is a kind of ability check that doesn't involve any die rolls.\"]\n['THE THREE TYPES OF CHECKS', \"How do you determine a character's passive score?\", \"A character's passive score is 10 + all modifiers that normally apply to the check. If the character has advantage, add 5. For disadvantage, subtrac